WEBVTT

00:03.138 --> 00:05.020
Welcome to the Life Church Podcast.

00:06.442 --> 00:11.587
We are in Acts 2.42 community, a family on a mission to bring a life of Jesus to warranty.

00:13.129 --> 00:20.817
We hope you're ready to hear what God has to say to you today through His Word and by His Spirit.

00:20.837 --> 00:28.786
We are looking at the Roman Road series, which is about how salvation works as the Apostle Paul teaches in the book of Romans.

00:29.538 --> 00:33.323
And I'm going to return to an analogy today a few different times.

00:34.043 --> 00:36.166
And I guess this is kind of a trigger warning.

00:36.206 --> 00:37.568
It's a medical analogy.

00:37.648 --> 00:42.874
If you're struggling with health care issues, that could be not the most fun analogy.

00:42.934 --> 00:46.578
But I think it's the best one that describes what we're talking about.

00:46.598 --> 00:49.302
Anyone here work for the NHS or for health care?

00:49.362 --> 00:50.503
Thank you for all that you do.

00:50.583 --> 00:51.304
I appreciate it.

00:51.945 --> 00:56.210
And of course, most of us then know what it's like to have to go to get

00:56.322 --> 01:00.728
treatment or to go to have a doctor look at us for some reason.

01:00.748 --> 01:05.454
And so within that world, you always have the symptoms, whatever we're experiencing.

01:06.055 --> 01:16.149
And then you have the actual underlying disease that is whatever the doctor hopefully will be able to tell you what the actual reason is that you're experiencing those symptoms.

01:16.910 --> 01:22.317
And then there's, there's treatment, but before the treatment, there has to be payment.

01:22.558 --> 01:25.842
Now, again, with the NHS, see, okay, I'm not from here.

01:26.402 --> 01:27.183
I'm not from here.

01:27.544 --> 01:35.397
So for me, when in America, when we would go to see the doctor, before you even saw the doctor, they would make sure you could pay the doctor.

01:35.858 --> 01:43.951
Whether they would check your health insurance, or they would check that you would be able to do it, or you had to pay, and then you could be made well, hopefully.

01:44.392 --> 01:46.655
Whereas here, of course, it's not that way.

01:46.716 --> 01:50.642
But of course, everyone that raised your hand that says you work for the NHS, obviously

01:50.754 --> 01:53.739
you get paid, which means there is a cost, right?

01:54.300 --> 01:59.388
Someone pays the cost, it's through taxes, through other means, but there is a cost to the treatment.

02:00.049 --> 02:07.941
And so when we're looking at the Romans' road through this lens, you have week one where we talked about all have sinned, all have sinned.

02:07.961 --> 02:18.738
This was both the symptoms and the disease for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God, for the wages of sin is death, for the verses that we looked at.

02:19.810 --> 02:22.094
And this was the bad news before the good news.

02:22.174 --> 02:26.782
This was the doctor sitting us down and telling us the problem that explains our symptoms.

02:27.383 --> 02:30.148
And we might not like it, but this is a necessary part of the process.

02:30.889 --> 02:37.321
In this case, the disease that explains all the symptoms of our life, why we're dying is sin.

02:38.062 --> 02:42.610
It's a mixture of our own sin and just the toxic sin soup you can

02:42.722 --> 02:44.104
trademark that, I just made it up.

02:44.665 --> 02:51.837
The sin soup of humanity that we cooperate to just make life miserable for each other, that's the issue.

02:51.897 --> 02:58.067
But the same doctor also has a treatment plan that has 100% success rate.

02:58.608 --> 02:59.470
Are you thankful for that?

03:00.011 --> 03:04.959
And that's what we started talking about last week, which week two was Christ died for us.

03:05.419 --> 03:06.962
This was the payment.

03:07.490 --> 03:11.735
Christ died for us, but God demonstrates his own love for us in this.

03:11.835 --> 03:14.838
While we were still sinners, Christ died for us.

03:15.198 --> 03:23.668
Before you could pay him back, before you earned it or owed it or anything like that, Jesus took care of the payment with his own death.

03:23.768 --> 03:24.729
Are you thankful for that?

03:25.770 --> 03:26.651
But here's the catch.

03:27.192 --> 03:28.113
Here's the catch.

03:28.673 --> 03:32.978
You need to take the treatment in order for it to be effective.

03:33.826 --> 03:40.416
Imagine if you had a serious health issue and you went to the doctor and the doctor diagnosed it properly and said, okay, here's the treatment plan.

03:40.436 --> 03:41.858
We're going to have surgery on this date.

03:41.878 --> 03:43.521
You're going to have this medication.

03:44.041 --> 03:47.286
And then we go, yeah, I can't be bothered.

03:47.306 --> 03:48.228
I don't want to get off my couch.

03:48.869 --> 03:50.591
I'm just leave the treatment there.

03:50.932 --> 04:03.250
Now we can kind of like laugh at that a bit, but then we realize that actually happens both in real life and in our spiritual lives because sometimes the treatment is invasive and the treatment kind of scares us.

04:03.906 --> 04:08.932
But the treatment is what is needed, and we have to trust the doctor in this case.

04:09.493 --> 04:11.796
So what is the treatment?

04:12.276 --> 04:13.658
Paul says it has two parts.

04:14.159 --> 04:16.502
In Romans 10, 9, it is confess and believe.

04:16.862 --> 04:19.385
Let's read it together from the screen.

04:19.425 --> 04:20.747
We'll do this a few times today.

04:20.787 --> 04:22.369
Romans 10, 9, let's say it.

04:22.910 --> 04:26.514
If you confess with your mouth, Jesus is Lord.

04:26.594 --> 04:31.702
and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.

04:32.183 --> 04:36.469
I always forget I have an accent until we talk together and I'm like, I can't even speak.

04:37.170 --> 04:42.258
Anyway, confess and believe, confess and believe.

04:42.799 --> 04:43.700
So let's break it down.

04:44.121 --> 04:45.543
Let's start with confess.

04:47.586 --> 04:55.218
When we think of applying salvation to our lives and when we talk about confessing, usually we think of admitting sin.

04:56.162 --> 04:57.504
repentance, that kind of thing.

04:57.784 --> 05:06.376
We think of 1 John 1, 9, where John tells us, if we confess our sins, he's faithful and just and will forgive us our sins and purify us from all unrighteousness.

05:06.416 --> 05:08.599
And of course, that is 100% true.

05:09.300 --> 05:10.822
But that's not what Paul says here.

05:10.882 --> 05:14.086
He says, if we confess, Jesus is Lord.

05:15.268 --> 05:17.571
So what does confessing actually mean?

05:18.853 --> 05:22.898
Confessing simply means to declare something publicly is true.

05:23.426 --> 05:25.509
to declare something publicly is true.

05:25.890 --> 05:29.415
So if you confess your sins, you're saying, yep, I did that.

05:30.697 --> 05:32.660
That's on me, I'm a sinner.

05:33.141 --> 05:36.045
You're saying that publicly, that's confessing our sins.

05:36.766 --> 05:44.338
But if you're saying Jesus is Lord, if you're confessing Jesus is Lord, you're saying publicly, yes, Jesus has authority over my life.

05:45.119 --> 05:49.746
Jesus has authority over my life and I can say that publicly.

05:50.914 --> 05:52.696
So what is it to be saved?

05:52.716 --> 05:55.080
Do we confess our sins or do we confess Jesus as Lord?

05:55.120 --> 05:56.482
Well, of course it's both.

05:57.323 --> 06:02.189
But why does Paul focus on lordship in this verse?

06:02.209 --> 06:06.215
I think it's simply this because our allegiance matters.

06:07.336 --> 06:09.119
Our allegiance matters.

06:10.721 --> 06:15.247
Confession of sin is definitely part of the plan of salvation, but it isn't the whole.

06:16.569 --> 06:17.330
There are

06:17.666 --> 06:24.757
Christian traditions that really emphasize the confession of sin, maybe to a spiritual leader or to a priest so that we can be forgiven.

06:25.378 --> 06:27.141
And this is fine, this is good and proper.

06:27.221 --> 06:34.693
But if all we focus on is confession and forgiveness, it can leave the allegiance of our heart unchanged.

06:36.055 --> 06:41.644
Because we can just believe, well, God will just forgive any sin as long as I just confess and ask for forgiveness.

06:42.345 --> 06:45.330
And then our life can just remain under our own lordship

06:45.666 --> 06:51.714
And Jesus just becomes the kind-hearted doormat that we just trample on and assume he'll just forgive us because he said he would.

06:51.754 --> 06:54.918
That's not the way it's supposed to work.

06:54.958 --> 06:56.620
I think we can all agree with that.

06:57.341 --> 06:59.464
This is how confession is supposed to work.

06:59.844 --> 07:01.386
It's a change of allegiance.

07:01.847 --> 07:07.394
It's saying, X, something used to be my Lord, but now Jesus is.

07:08.475 --> 07:10.738
Sin used to be my Lord.

07:11.202 --> 07:14.386
But now Jesus is, I don't want sin to be my Lord anymore.

07:14.506 --> 07:18.131
I'm confessing my sin and now I want Jesus to be my Lord.

07:18.432 --> 07:20.254
Selfishness has been my Lord.

07:20.635 --> 07:22.157
Pride has been my Lord.

07:22.337 --> 07:24.320
Comfort has been my Lord.

07:25.061 --> 07:28.666
The approval of others has been my Lord, but not anymore.

07:30.168 --> 07:30.748
Jesus is.

07:32.971 --> 07:39.220
But it goes beyond just rejecting any of the internal rule of various things in our lives.

07:39.260 --> 07:40.882
It's also about Jesus

07:40.962 --> 07:45.307
being the supreme authority over any other external authority.

07:45.868 --> 07:49.472
You know, Paul wrote this letter to the church in Rome.

07:50.273 --> 07:52.375
This was the capital of the empire.

07:52.956 --> 07:56.400
If we're talking Star Wars, this is Coruscant, okay?

07:56.740 --> 07:59.423
This is the capital of the empire.

07:59.503 --> 08:08.594
It was extremely significant because the summary statement of Roman power of the day was simply Caesar's Lord.

08:09.890 --> 08:10.911
Caesar is Lord.

08:11.852 --> 08:15.016
And this was a common phrase used in all levels of society.

08:15.056 --> 08:16.398
This was part of daily life.

08:16.959 --> 08:20.223
It was a statement of royal power saying that Caesar is king.

08:20.283 --> 08:32.638
It was a statement of spiritual power because Caesar's past were venerated as gods and even Caesar's presence sometimes were venerated as a god while they were still alive.

08:32.998 --> 08:35.641
So it was a statement of spiritual power.

08:36.162 --> 08:39.506
And basically it just publicly identified you as a good citizen.

08:40.450 --> 08:42.533
It just publicly identified you as a good citizen.

08:42.573 --> 08:46.217
If you could say Caesar is Lord, you could go about your normal life.

08:47.098 --> 08:50.883
Caesar is Lord was the password to living a normal life.

08:52.666 --> 08:55.349
But as Christians, we don't get the password to a normal life.

08:56.591 --> 08:58.273
We get the password to eternal life.

08:59.514 --> 09:03.559
And that public password is Jesus is Lord.

09:04.981 --> 09:08.786
Because allegiance isn't allegiance if it remains private.

09:10.178 --> 09:10.398
Right?

09:11.800 --> 09:15.325
Allegiance is an allegiance if it just remains private.

09:18.749 --> 09:24.877
Now, was Paul encouraging the Roman Christians to just rebel and to burn down the society?

09:24.937 --> 09:26.479
Of course not.

09:27.320 --> 09:35.090
In fact, in chapter 13, he clearly encourages Christians to fully participate in civic life, to pay their taxes, to pray for

09:35.202 --> 09:41.869
the governing authorities to respect governing authorities as something God had set up to help humanity flourish.

09:42.890 --> 09:44.572
Paul himself was a Roman citizen.

09:44.672 --> 09:48.436
Paul himself would appeal to Caesar as part of his legal proceedings.

09:49.778 --> 09:54.643
The only thing to withhold from Caesar was ultimate allegiance.

09:54.663 --> 09:57.246
That was to be reserved for Jesus alone.

09:58.367 --> 09:59.809
Jesus himself said, what?

10:00.329 --> 10:02.531
Give to Caesar, what is Caesar's?

10:02.792 --> 10:04.914
But give to God.

10:05.346 --> 10:06.888
what belongs to God.

10:07.750 --> 10:09.012
Caesar can have your taxes.

10:10.133 --> 10:11.075
It pays for the NHS.

10:13.058 --> 10:14.740
But God gets our allegiance.

10:17.044 --> 10:24.575
Now, I don't believe that Paul is saying that we just have to walk around every day and every time we tap our card to the till go, Jesus is Lord.

10:25.817 --> 10:26.418
Jesus is Lord.

10:26.478 --> 10:31.826
Okay, it doesn't have to be this thing we're just constantly saying, like a mantra.

10:32.898 --> 10:36.803
There's wisdom, there's nuance, and how we share it depending on context.

10:36.923 --> 10:48.937
But when push comes to shove, and there's a direct challenge to what we believe, or a direct challenge on who to obey, there could only be one answer, and that is Jesus is Lord.

10:49.998 --> 10:55.125
And of course, we show this very publicly at one time events, like our public baptism.

10:55.465 --> 10:59.730
That's us saying publicly to the whole world, whoever's here, Jesus is Lord.

10:59.906 --> 11:05.934
There's quiet ways, though, to say it, like acting with integrity, acting with honesty, and all our public dealings.

11:06.535 --> 11:15.468
If we're asked by our employer to do something that Jesus would not do, we need to politely and firmly assert that we have a different authority that we answer to.

11:15.508 --> 11:25.522
And in normal conversation, when people want us to be like them and how they live, how they love, how they speak, we lovingly stand firm in our allegiance to Jesus.

11:26.434 --> 11:29.659
Of course, there's many biblical examples of this, both positive and negative.

11:30.360 --> 11:44.442
Probably the biggest positive example we have is in the book of Daniel with Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who were told, of course, they were captives living, they were Jews that now lived in Babylon, but they were working within that government system.

11:44.922 --> 11:50.771
And of course, Nebuchadnezzar decides to build a statue of himself and say, everyone has to bow down and worship me in the form of a statue.

11:51.473 --> 11:55.058
And at the time, the password, so to speak, was

11:55.234 --> 11:57.257
Nebuchadnezzar is Lord, and I will bow down.

11:58.018 --> 12:01.682
But they didn't use that password, and they passed the test, right?

12:02.343 --> 12:04.506
They were thrown into the fiery furnace, but God rescued them.

12:04.866 --> 12:05.447
That was great.

12:05.547 --> 12:06.769
Why were they able to do that?

12:06.849 --> 12:08.391
Well, I think God helped them.

12:08.731 --> 12:11.235
I think they had some courage, of course, on their own.

12:11.615 --> 12:13.037
But also, they had practice.

12:14.379 --> 12:16.181
They grew up as a minority culture.

12:16.201 --> 12:18.544
They were captives, remember, in Babylon?

12:19.145 --> 12:23.250
They had developed the muscle memory of counter-cultural loyalty.

12:24.034 --> 12:27.458
They had developed the muscle memory of counter-cultural loyalty.

12:27.478 --> 12:28.860
They had practice.

12:28.880 --> 12:30.322
This was different from Peter.

12:31.343 --> 12:35.429
You see, Peter, he lived all his life as a majority culture.

12:36.029 --> 12:45.842
Yes, Rome was really in charge over Palestine at the time, but if you were a Jew growing up in Judea in the first century,

12:46.082 --> 12:48.966
And everybody you knew was a Jew, pretty much.

12:49.447 --> 12:52.731
And the password to normal life in your society was the Shema.

12:53.112 --> 12:55.756
Hero Israel, the Lord our God, the Lord is one.

12:55.856 --> 12:59.161
And he would have passed that test every day of the week, right?

13:00.402 --> 13:07.432
But when Jesus comes on the scene, Peter has the revelation that the one Lord that he was already loyal to, that one Lord was Jesus.

13:09.575 --> 13:14.322
And on the night of Jesus' trial, Peter finds himself in a situation he's never been in before.

13:16.002 --> 13:22.068
People, his own people, are recognizing that he had been with Jesus and he had a choice.

13:23.249 --> 13:25.811
He could be truthful about it or not.

13:27.293 --> 13:31.197
And three times he denied even knowing Jesus.

13:32.358 --> 13:40.245
Now if a Roman soldier had come into that courtyard and said bow down to Caesar, Peter would have given his life right at that moment.

13:41.587 --> 13:42.628
But that's not what was happening.

13:43.809 --> 13:45.010
People were just asking him,

13:45.986 --> 13:46.907
Hey, do you know Jesus?

13:49.992 --> 13:50.793
And he failed the test.

13:54.539 --> 13:56.502
So what's it like in 21st century England?

13:58.365 --> 14:01.310
What's normal life more like?

14:04.975 --> 14:07.439
I know Sheila and I have talked to Grace.

14:07.479 --> 14:11.986
She goes to a church of England, high school down in Northwich.

14:12.066 --> 14:19.677
And of course, we chose that school not because we knew it would be a paragon of Christianity, but just because we didn't want it to be anti-God if at all possible.

14:19.717 --> 14:20.358
And it's not.

14:20.578 --> 14:22.741
It's a good school, good teachers.

14:24.003 --> 14:26.667
But we asked her, is it hard to be a Christian in your school?

14:26.847 --> 14:29.331
And she said, yeah, so in what ways?

14:29.491 --> 14:32.676
She's like, well, we have these RE lessons or religious education.

14:33.036 --> 14:33.657
Those are fine.

14:34.278 --> 14:36.882
But then when it's just the students talking,

14:37.122 --> 14:42.309
around a table kind of quizzing each other on doctrinal issues that they have to get right for the test.

14:44.612 --> 14:51.903
The way they always preface it is, well, not that I believe this, but this is the doctrine of Christianity.

14:51.923 --> 14:58.852
And then the next person, well, not that I believe this, but of course Jesus rose from the dead or whatever the answer is.

14:59.794 --> 15:00.455
And that's hard.

15:01.396 --> 15:02.237
Isn't that hard?

15:02.257 --> 15:05.682
I mean, we pray for our youth, right?

15:06.082 --> 15:09.506
But pray for ourselves because isn't that kind of what we normally face?

15:09.846 --> 15:16.433
I think the password to normal life nowadays is kind of something like, well, I don't really know Jesus, but I know about him.

15:18.155 --> 15:19.717
That's kind of the password to normal life.

15:19.737 --> 15:26.164
You mark yourself out as different if you actually say, Jesus actually matters to me, not just that I'm aware that he existed.

15:28.206 --> 15:32.050
So I could keep going on about confessing, but I think we need to get to talking about believing.

15:32.130 --> 15:33.131
Let's talk about believing.

15:33.652 --> 15:36.896
Reminder, our stop on the Roman road today is Romans 10, 9.

15:36.957 --> 15:38.018
Let's say it again together.

15:39.079 --> 15:50.635
So how do we apply the cure to our lives?

15:50.815 --> 15:53.279
As we already talked about it, we shift our allegiance.

15:53.339 --> 15:55.762
That's part one of the treatment plan.

15:56.258 --> 15:58.000
But why would we shift that allegiance?

15:58.160 --> 16:03.926
Well, the only reason to shift your allegiance is if you actually believe Jesus is who he says he is, right?

16:04.627 --> 16:10.153
If you think that I'm lying or you think I'm mistaken about who Jesus is, please don't shift your allegiance.

16:10.254 --> 16:11.715
Please don't declare Jesus is Lord.

16:12.176 --> 16:14.298
That would just be succumbing to positive peer pressure.

16:15.019 --> 16:16.641
You know, all the cool kids believe in Jesus.

16:16.661 --> 16:17.361
So I want you to.

16:17.802 --> 16:21.446
That's not the reason we're supposed to believe in Jesus.

16:21.586 --> 16:25.170
No, the change of allegiance comes out of a change of belief.

16:25.378 --> 16:25.698
Right?

16:26.119 --> 16:28.662
The change of allegiance comes out a change of belief.

16:28.762 --> 16:31.104
Belief is the second part of the treatment plan.

16:31.705 --> 16:35.589
Now, note, Paul does not say, believe that Jesus died.

16:36.870 --> 16:38.592
He just skipped straight to resurrection.

16:39.473 --> 16:45.780
And I think this is because the facts of Jesus' death on a cross in Jerusalem were well established at the time.

16:46.421 --> 16:48.143
It was in the records of Pontius Pilate.

16:48.203 --> 16:50.125
It was in the living memory of thousands of people.

16:50.545 --> 16:54.930
And it was not a stretch to believe that Rome crucified someone who claimed to be a king.

16:55.330 --> 17:02.537
Everybody believed Jesus died, but to believe God raised him from the dead, that's a bit of a different story.

17:04.479 --> 17:10.885
Now, there were also hundreds of eyewitnesses that gave eyewitness testimony to the resurrected Jesus as well.

17:11.265 --> 17:15.469
He hung around for 40 days before ascending to heaven, so this was not done in secret.

17:16.630 --> 17:24.978
But come on now, someone coming back to life after being dead for three days, and not just mostly dead, all dead.

17:25.410 --> 17:27.352
That's a princess bride reference if you missed that.

17:29.495 --> 17:32.739
That person coming back to life, someone who was brutally dead.

17:35.002 --> 17:38.707
And even if you spoke with people who saw him, you'd still struggle to believe it, right?

17:38.767 --> 17:39.468
Just like Thomas.

17:40.509 --> 17:41.250
Can we be honest?

17:41.290 --> 17:43.072
That would be hard to believe.

17:44.894 --> 17:46.577
It does strain belief.

17:48.058 --> 17:49.440
But that is the point.

17:50.762 --> 17:54.066
There is no point believing that Jesus did something believable.

17:55.810 --> 17:56.110
Right?

17:56.872 --> 17:57.773
That he's just a human.

17:58.654 --> 18:00.397
We are saying that Jesus is God.

18:00.597 --> 18:05.064
So for him to prove that he's God, he has to do something that otherwise wouldn't be possible, right?

18:05.504 --> 18:10.932
If Jesus stayed dead, his teaching would just have been this misguided love prophet in the wilderness.

18:11.012 --> 18:12.575
We would just kind of have forgotten about him.

18:13.035 --> 18:18.564
But it was his resurrection and those that believed in his resurrection that turned the world upside down.

18:18.924 --> 18:22.930
Resurrection is the proof that Jesus is who he says he is.

18:24.866 --> 18:27.549
And then Paul says, we need to believe this in our heart.

18:29.331 --> 18:35.457
The Greek word for heart is cardia, which means heart.

18:37.799 --> 18:39.301
Waiting, no one thinks that's funny.

18:39.561 --> 18:40.622
I think that's funny.

18:40.642 --> 18:41.863
Cardia, cardio means heart.

18:42.264 --> 18:46.268
It can also generally refers to our thoughts and our feelings.

18:46.848 --> 18:52.434
And so we could talk about going from a head knowledge to a heart knowledge, but I don't really think the Greek

18:52.610 --> 18:54.833
culture of the time would have made those distinctions.

18:55.734 --> 18:58.297
But cardia can also mean the middle.

18:59.218 --> 19:00.920
It can mean the core of something.

19:01.641 --> 19:06.367
Think of the way we use the phrase the heart of the matter, getting to the heart of the matter.

19:07.668 --> 19:18.802
When the Bible says that we need to believe something in our heart or love someone from the heart, it's saying that it needs to be from the core of our person, from the core of our person.

19:18.946 --> 19:25.696
Another way of saying it is this, belief in the resurrection needs to become the foundational truth of our lives.

19:26.297 --> 19:31.144
Belief in the resurrection needs to become the foundational truth of our lives.

19:32.085 --> 19:41.559
In 1 Corinthians 10, Paul is very clear, Christianity as a belief system completely unravels without the resurrection of Jesus.

19:42.079 --> 19:44.162
Let's not pretend there's any other way around this.

19:44.443 --> 19:46.706
If Jesus wasn't raised from the dead, we should just all go home.

19:47.906 --> 19:49.148
And if you wanna leave, you can.

19:49.228 --> 19:49.849
